1 (b) Provide resources to schools to facilitate the athletic
2 development and guidance of pupils who participate in a
3 sanctioned sport; and
4 (c) Provide wrap-around services.
5 2. The Nevada Interscholastic Activities Association may
6 accept gifts, grants and donations from any source for deposit in
7 the Fund.
8 3. The interest and income earned on the money in the Fund,
9 after deducting any applicable charges, must be credited to the
10 Fund.
11 4. The Executive Director of the Nevada Interscholastic
12 Activities Association shall, on or before July 1 of each year:
13 (a) Prepare a report that describes:
14 (1) The total amount of money deposited in the Fund;
15 (2) Any expenditures of money made from the Fund; and
16 (3) Progress made in achieving the goals of the Fund set
17 forth in subsection 1; and
18 (b) Submit the report to the Director of the Legislative Counsel
19 Bureau for transmittal to the Joint Interim Standing Committee
20 on Education.
21 5. As used in this section, “wrap-around services” means
22 support services provided to pupils who participate in a sanctioned
23 sport, including, without limitation, tutoring or other supplemental
24 academic achievement programs, college and career counseling
25 and mentoring.
26 Sec. 4. 1. The Nevada Interscholastic Activities Association
27 shall study the development of pupils as athletes in this State and the
28 infrastructure necessary to develop a pipeline to transform pupils
29 who participate in a sanctioned sport into professional athletes. The
30 study must include, without limitation:
31 (a) A review of existing:
32 (1) Athletic facilities, including, without limitation, practice
33 facilities, arenas, stadiums, playing fields and playing surfaces;
34 (2) Resources for coaches; and
35 (3) Athletic programs at schools which are members of the
36 Nevada Interscholastic Activities Association; and
37 (b) An examination of, and recommendations for:
38 (1) Legislation to promote the ability of Nevada to produce
39 professional athletes;
40 (2) A statewide program to promote participation in sports,
41 including, without limitation, lacrosse, for pupils in underserved
42 communities; and
43 (3) Establishing wrap-around services in public schools to
44 promote academic achievement and the development of life skills
45 for pupils who are athletes.
